1079","1115":"1115","1049":"1049","1069":"1069","1079":"1079","1045":"1045","1132":"1132","1087":"1087","1075":"1075","1074":"1074","1083":"1083","Peronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France","Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France","Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Melun, Seine-et-Marne, France":"Melun, Seine-et-Marne, France","Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Péronne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Pasquale, Angelo, Deno, Dino, Francesco, Orazio, Vito.","Italian: from an augmentative of the personal name   Pero  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pero","meanings":["Italian: from the personal name <i>Pero</i>, a variant of <i>Piero</i> ‘Peter’ (see   Pieri  ).","Galician: from the personal name <i>Pero</i>, Galician equivalent of   Peter  .","Portuguese: habitational name from any of the places called Pero."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Péronne II was born in 1045, in Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France as the son of Robert DE PERONNE and Alix DE FRANCIE. He married Berthilde d'Avesnes in 1074. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1087, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1045–1087":"1045–1087","1049–1115":"1049–1115","1069–Female":"1069–Surnud","1075–1132":"1075–1132","–Male":"Surnud","–1083":"–1083","–1079":"–1079","1115":"1115","1049":"1049","1069":"1069","1079":"1079","1045":"1045","1132":"1132","1087":"1087","1075":"1075","1074":"1074","1083":"1083","Peronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Melun, Seine-et-Marne, France":"Melun, Seine-et-Marne, Prantsusmaa","Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1045–1087":"1045–1087","1049–1115":"1049–1115","1069–Female":"1069–Kuollut","1075–1132":"1075–1132","–Male":"Kuollut","–1083":"–1083","–1079":"–1079","1115":"1115","1049":"1049","1069